model_explanation: the prosodic focus on "ROB" in S1 means that Sam did not give apples to anyone else besides Rob, which entails that Sam didn’t give Sue apples.

the prosodic focus on "SUE" in S1 means that Sam only gave grapes to Sue and did not give grapes to anyone else. S2 talks about giving oranges, which is unrelated to the restriction in S1, so the statements are independent.

the focus on “SUE” in S1 means that Sam only gave grapes to Sue and didn’t give anyone else grapes. Since S1 doesn’t specify that Sue got anything other than grapes, S2 (saying Sam didn’t give Sue bananas) is consistent and entailed by S1.
with the focus on "MARY," S1 means that only Mary received grapes, and no one else did. S2 contradicts this by stating that Ellen also received grapes.

the focus on "ROB" in S1 means that only Rob received oranges (and no one else got oranges). This doesn’t restrict what else Rob might receive, so S2, about bananas, is independent and not contradictory or entailed.
the focus on "SUE" means that only Sue got bananas and no one else got bananas. It also implies that Sue didn’t get anything else besides bananas, so S2 (that Sue didn't get grapes) is entailed.
the focus on "TOM" means that Sam only gave grapes to Tom and didn’t give anyone else grapes. As a result, it follows that Tom did not get apples, so S2 is entailed by S1.
the prosodic focus on "TOM" means that only Tom received bananas, and it implies that Tom didn’t receive anything else (like grapes). Therefore, S2 is entailed by S1.
with the focus on "ROB," S1 means that only Rob got apples, and no one else got apples. It also implies that Rob only got apples and nothing else. S2 contradicts this by saying Rob also got grapes.

if the focus is on "ELLEN," it means that only Ellen received grapes, and no one else received grapes. It also implies that Ellen only received grapes and nothing else, so S2 (saying Ellen also got oranges) contradicts S1.
